<p>
The first step to writing your <a href="JavaScript:Gloss('20');">citations</a> is choosing a <a href="JavaScript:Gloss('21');">style</a> to follow. 
</p>
<h2>How to choose a style? </h2>
<p>
Always ask your instructors which style they prefer. As you take more and more classes in different departments though, you'll notice that certain disciplines tend to use certain styles. So, if you're taking English 10, chances are you'll need to use the Modern Language Association (MLA) style. If you're taking Psych 10, you'll probably need to use the American Psychological Association (APA) style. Whichever style you choose, be sure to use it throughout your paper&mdash;be consistent. 
</p>
<h2>Some styles to choose from include:</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<a href="http://www.apa.org/" target="_blank">American Psychological Association (APA)</a>&mdash;used in the social sciences
</li>
<li>
<a href="http://www.press.uchicago.edu/Misc/Chicago/cmosfaq/cmosfaq.html" target="_blank">Chicago Manual of Style</a>&mdash;used in the social sciences and humanities
</li>
<li>
<a href="http://www.councilscienceeditors.org" target="_blank">Council of Science Editors (CSE)</a>&mdash;used in the sciences 
</li>
<li>
<a href="http://www.mla.org/" target="_blank">Modern Language Association (MLA)</a>&mdash;for the arts and humanities 
</li>
</ul>

<p>
Need more? <a href="../06/01.cfm" target="_blank">See Resources for UCLA Students</a>.
</p>



